(150, 'Renoise', '200 OK', 891, 'http://www.renoise.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Renoise is the next generation of music tracker software, combining studio quality sound and virtually infinite expandability with a clear and concise interface putting every parameter and option literally at your fingertips!\r\n\r\nWhile using proven Amiga music tracker technology, Renoise fully supports MIDI and embraces modern and limitless VST plug-in / VST instrument technologies, therefore achieving power and precision every electronic musician had been dreaming about in one music software.\r\n\r\nIn over 3 years of development we listened to all of you users and implemented all suggestions into Renoise, therefore building powerful and reliable music software that suits your needs!', 'Music', 'Tracker', NULL, 0, '2002-03-12 00:00:00', 0),
(151, 'Impulse Tracker', 'Connection Failure.  Status code unavailable.', 1024, 'http://www.users.on.net/~jtlim/ImpulseTracker/', NULL, NULL, 'Impulse Tracker is a revolutionary new music tracker under development in South Australia by Jeffrey Lim (Pulse/PoP). It is quite similar to the popular Scream Tracker by Future Crew, and is therefore quite easy to learn. In fact, if you''re already experienced in Scream Tracker, then the switch to Impulse Tracker can happen in a matter of minutes!', 'Music', 'Tracker', 0, 0, '2002-03-12 00:00:00', 0),
(152, 'Old Computers', '302 Object moved - <a href="news/default.asp">news/default.asp</a>', 827, 'http://www.old-computers.com', NULL, NULL, 'Thierry Schembri and Olivier Boisseau met in a pub in London in 1973. They both were fond of computers and teddy-bears. They spoke for hours and finally concluded that teddy-bears were not a particularly interesting hobby. So they decided to focus on computers. Then they left the bar and never saw each others for years.\r\n<br />\r\nThen in 1998, in a little french village, they met again in a an "old-computers collectors meeting". They spoke about the good old time and laughed about the fact that they once were fascinated by teddy-bears, though Thierry was still an active member of the "anonymous teddy-bears collectors"...\r\n<br />\r\nThey learned that they were both developping sites devoted to old-computers and decided that they would be much more effective if they merged these two excellent web-sites.\r\n<br />\r\nThough the two friends were separated by millions of kilometers (Thierry lived in the Artic area, and Olivier on a beach with palms), they quickly started their new project and soon produced something very funky.\r\n<br />\r\nAt the start of 2001, they officialy launched their new site and received many congratulations from all around the world !', 'Old School', 'Computers', 5, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(153, 'Digital Press - The Video Game Database', '200 OK', 715, 'http://www.digitpress.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Digital Press Online is dedicated to the "Pac-rats" among video gamers... short attention spans, library-sized collections, consoles precariously wired in spider-web fashion... Sound like you? Check around - we cover just about everything "retro" including Atari, Intellivision, ColecoVision, Vectrex, Odyssey, Nintendo, and Sega Master System as well as all of the most recent consoles.', 'Old School', 'Games', 4, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(154, 'Atari History Museum', '200 OK', 746, 'http://www.atarimuseum.com', NULL, NULL, 'This site provides information, images and personal stories on all items produced by Atari as well as news and links to further assist any and all individuals interested in learning more about the company that helped to pioneer and shape many areas of Video Arcade Entertainment, Home Consumer Electronics, Personal Computer Systems and much, much more..', 'Old School', 'Computers', 4, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(155, 'History of Computing', '200 OK', 655, 'http://www.thocp.net/', NULL, NULL, 'The purpose of this site is to tell the story of computing. What was needed to come to the computing machines we know today. What technology was used and who made that possible. What other developments drove the need for computing.', 'Old School', 'Computers', 5, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(156, 'Old Computer Dot Com', '200 OK', 820, 'http://www.theoldcomputer.com/', NULL, NULL, 'This site is dedicated to all aspects of retro computing, collecting and gaming. In here you will find a large collection of emulators for many weird and defunked formats, Rom''s for all the major retro consoles and computers as well as library''s full of material like commercials, magazines and manuals.', 'Old School', 'Computers', 4, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(157, 'Vintage Computer Ads', '200 OK', 653, 'http://www.vintagecomputerads.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Welcome to Vintage computer ads! We launched April 27th 2001.With your support we can make this into the definitive vintage ad site on the net. We now host over 350 vintage computer ads from IBM to Apple, Commodore, to Atari and hundreds of other hardware  ads. Electronic Arts, Epyx, Activision, and all the wonderful software companies. Many of us are in our late twenties and grew up with these systems. Seeing the ads brings back floods of memories. Thanks everyone. Here''s to our continued success!', 'Old School', 'Computers', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(158, 'Machine Room', '200 OK', 829, 'http://www.machine-room.org/', NULL, NULL, 'Interested in retrocomputing, computer collecting, or computer history? Are you nostalgic and pining for Ye Olden Days? Well, then, welcome to the Machine Room, the ever-expanding database of old computers. Here you''ll find technical specifications, descriptions, trivia, and pictures of so-called obsolete computers from a horde of manufacturers, as well as links to more information. \r\nThis site pays homage to the wonderful days when ''computer'' didn''t mean ''IBM PC clone'' and 4 kilobytes really made a difference. The Machine Room was conceived in late 1994 and established in 1995 (this is the sixth major revision of the contents, appearance and user interface). It has been a personal project since its inception, and is a free site.', 'Old School', 'Computers', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(159, 'Oldbits Computer Museum', '200 OK', 553, 'http://oldbits.de/', NULL, NULL, 'This WWW - Museum is a virtual exhibition of a real existing collection of old computers and videogames and it is located between Leipzig and Dessau. \r\nPlease have a look at the items in the museum and enjoy!', 'Old School', 'Computers', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(160, 'Retro Base', '200 OK', 718, 'http://www.retrobase.net/', NULL, NULL, 'Welcome to RetroBase.com, a website devoted to the preservation of classic videogames. We have large archives of games with product info and screenshots.', 'Old School', 'Games', 4, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(161, 'ZZap Back Magazine', '200 OK', 614, 'http://www.zzap.w2s.co.uk/', NULL, NULL, 'A tribute page to the C64 magazine Zzap .', 'Old School', 'Magazines', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(162, 'Old Computer Magazine', '200 OK', 879, 'http://www.old-computer-mags.co.uk/', NULL, NULL, 'Are you nostalgic about computer magazines from the 80''s? Do the phrases "Crash Smash" and "Zzap! Sizzler" mean anything to you? If so, welcome - you''ve come to the right place!', 'Old School', 'Magazines', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(163, 'A Def Guide to Zzap!64', '200 OK', 981, 'http://www.zzap64.co.uk/', NULL, NULL, 'ZZap! 64 was first launched in 1985, It came out as a fully games orientated magazine at a time when most other Commodore 64 magazines gave only marginal coverage to games. ZZap originally only contained C64 game reviews but by the latter part of 1988 Amiga games were covered from time to time. However, in issue 42 (October 1998), the Amiga became a permanent part of ZZap, well permanent that is until issue 74 (June 1991) when ZZap again returned to it''s original format of C64 games only.', 'Old School', 'Magazines', 4, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(164, 'Amiga Coverdisks', '200 OK', 955, 'http://amigacoverdisks.emuunlim.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Well, as you might have suspected, this page contains coverdisks of Amiga magazines for use with any Amiga emulator.\r\nThis site contains coverdisks of Amiga Action, The One, CU Amiga, Amiga Power, Amiga Computing and\r\nAmiga Format. I''m planning to add coverdisks of Amiga Games, Amiga Shopper, Amiga User International and some other magazines.', 'Old School', 'Magazines', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(165, 'Commadore Format Library', '200 OK', 869, 'http://www.commodoreformat.co.uk/', NULL, NULL, 'This site has been set up in memory of one of the best Commodore 64 Magazines of the 90s. Our main aim is to scan in all issues and make them available online. We will also be offering the covertapes that came with the magazines (which can be played on a PC using a suitable C64 emulator) as well as a searchable database of all games previewed, reviewed and "busted" in CF''s Hints and Tips section.', 'Old School', 'Magazines', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(166, 'Classic Gamer', '200 OK', 733, 'http://www.classicgamer.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Classic Gamer Magazine is an ongoing PDF e-publication dedicated to providing readers with an entertaining and informative look at video games from all eras', 'Old School', 'Information', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(167, 'Atari 2600 Landfill', '200 OK', 840, 'http://www.atari2600.net/', NULL, NULL, 'Welcome to the Atari 2600 Landfill, where I will dig up what many (including me) concider to be the greatist console game system in history. This is a little introduction to my site, I built it in FAQ style, trying to cover question I thought folks to ask.', 'Old School', 'Games', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(168, 'Atari Gaming HQ', '200 OK', 678, 'http://www.atarihq.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Welcome to the new look of the Atari Gaming Headquarters. After months of hard work, the new site is ready to go! You''ll notice a whole new perspective on Atari history and gaming here, and with more updates in the future you''re sure to find something new to learn all the time! Enjoy!', 'Old School', 'Games', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(169, 'SMS Tributes', '200 OK', 590, 'http://www.smstributes.co.uk/', NULL, NULL, ' Welcome to SMS Tributes a brand new SMS webpage, the aim of this site is to collect information about Sega Master System games bad and good', 'Old School', 'Games', 4, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(170, 'Apple-History.com', '200 OK', 601, 'http://www.apple-history.com/', NULL, NULL, 'This site is intended to provide a broad history of Apple Computer, Inc., from the invention of the Apple I in 1976 to the troubled times of the past few years to the current revival. I have attempted to be as accurate and comprehensive as possible in writing it, and it should be interesting to both novice and expert computer users.', 'Old School', 'Computers', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(171, 'OldSkool.Org', '200 OK', 1005, 'http://www.oldskool.org/', NULL, NULL, 'The concept of "Oldskool" is pretty much the entire foundation for this website. Specifically: Oldskool is my flavor of "Old school", a term commonly given to something that, while old, was (and still is) innovative, fresh, proper, clever, and generally correct and the right way to do things. The old school begets the new school (anything new and modern), for you certainly can''t get to anything new without going through the old. For example: Robotron is the old school, while Quake III is the new school; Sister Sledge is the old school, while En Vogue is the new school; and so on. Old school is, ultimately, a term of respect.', 'Old School', 'Computers', 3, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(172, 'Moby Games', '200 OK', 921, 'http://www.mobygames.com/', 'http://www.mobygames.com/rss/feeds', NULL, 'MobyGames is the working name of an extremely ambitious project: To meticulously catalog all relevant information about electronic games (computer, console, and arcade) on a game-by-game basis, and then offer up that information through flexible queries and "data mining". In layman''s terms, it''s a huge game database.', 'Old School', 'Games', 5, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', 0),
(173, 'TUOL', '200 OK', NULL, 'http://tuol.cjb.net/', NULL, NULL, 'It started in august 1999 with a mail from HaZZeL to me, Elwood. I had known him for some months - we were both running abandonware sites (or what was counted as that back then). He was asking me what I would think about opening up an alternative to the Abandonware Ring. Back then the AR was basically the only ring - with the exception of Abandonweb, which was a small webring (with a similar concept to today). The Ultimate OldwareZ Linkpage was founded.', 'Old School', 'Abandonedware', 4, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', -1),
(174, 'Abandoned Places', '200 OK', NULL, 'http://www.aplaces.org/', NULL, NULL, 'An Abandonedware Ring<br>\r\nRule 1.1<br>\r\nYour site may not contain any form of warez. Not old warez, not new warez. No warez. All the downloads on your site should be abandoned by the original copyright holders (where abandoned means no longer being sold and supported). Having other ways of distributing oldwarez through your own way (be it IRC, FTP or such) falls under this rule too.', 'Old School', 'Abandonedware', 0, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', -1),
(175, 'Desert of Oldies', '404 Not Found', NULL, 'http://koti.mbnet.fi/doo/', NULL, NULL, '"Desert of Oldies" is what you would call an abandonware ring. Our goal is to list sites that are abandonware related. If you don''t know what abandonware is then have a look around.', 'Old School', 'Abandonedware', 0, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', -1),
(176, 'Ring Of Truth', '503 Service Temporarily Unavailable', NULL, 'http://www.ringoftruth.tk/', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Old School', 'Abandonedware', NULL, 0, '2003-01-21 00:00:00', -1),
(177, 'Game Spot', '200 OK', 636, 'http://www.gamespot.com', 'http://www.gamespot.com/misc/rss/index.html', NULL, 'Since its launch in 1996, GameSpot has undergone two major redesigns and a few minor face-lifts. The site has received dozens of industry awards, but more importantly it has earned the respect and loyalty of the world''s biggest and best gaming audience. The entire staff is committed to serving the needs of that audience, and we work as hard as we can--day in and day out, year in and year out--to live up to our goal of being the first and best place "Where Gamers Go to Know."', 'Gaming', 'News', NULL, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(178, 'GameSpy News', '200 OK', 1028, 'http://www.gamespy.com/index/news.html', 'http://scripts.gamespy.com/rss/gamespy.all.2.0.xml', NULL, '24 Hour gaming news coverage from the inside.', 'Gaming', 'News', 0, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(179, 'Game FAQ', '200 OK', 765, 'http://www.gamefaqs.com/', NULL, NULL, 'GameFAQs was "born" on November 5, 1995 as the "Video Game FAQ Achive", after a long rainy weekend of work.', 'Gaming', 'FAQ', NULL, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(180, 'Adrenaline Vault', '200 OK', 797, 'http://www.avault.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Over one million people a month visit the Adrenaline Vault, making it one of the Top Ten gaming websites in the world, and the most recognized independent source of uninfluenced PC and video game information. The Adrenaline Vault, launched in 1995, is published daily by gamers, and is committed to excellence and honesty.', 'Gaming', 'News', NULL, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
