(197, 'ISO News', '200 OK', 1121, 'http://www.theisonews.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Welcome to the scenes first and only ISO news page. We opened up 12-07-98 when orm was bored at work and started to wonder why there were no iso release info sites. Immediately after opening, krazy8 joined the crew. After 6 hard months of working, orm retires and krazy8 retains sole leadership.', 'Gaming', 'Forum', 0, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(199, 'Razor 1911 Demo', '200 OK', 878, 'http://www.razor1911.com/', NULL, NULL, 'Razor 1911, the legendary group that has been around since 1985.', 'Art', 'Group', 4, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(200, 'LKCC', 'Connection Failure.  Status code unavailable.', 630, 'http://www.lkcc.org/', NULL, NULL, 'Nothing useful for more then a decade', 'Art', 'Group', 2, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(201, 'Tristar and Red Sector Inc.', '200 OK', 665, 'http://www.trsi.org', NULL, NULL, 'TRSI is an acronym for Tristar and Red Sector, Incorporated. Founded by a supplier from Germany who went under the pseudonym Irata [1] (http://noname.c64.org/csdb/scener/?id=4380), TRSI began in 1990 as a cooperative Commodore 64 demo coding and cracking group. The alliance between Tristar and Red Sector, Inc. was formed after different group members met up at KewL Party in Denmark.\r\n\r\nTRSI naturally migrated from the C64 release platform to the Amiga and IBM-PC, and even branched off into the console gaming scene. In the mid 1990s they created an independent record label, TRSI Records.', 'Art', 'Group', 3, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(203, 'ACiD Productions', '200 OK', 2452, 'http://www.acid.org/', NULL, NULL, 'ACiD Productions was originally founded in 1990 as ANSI Creators in Demand by five members: RaD Man, Shadow Demon, Grimm, The Beholder, and Phantom. Their work originally concentrated in ANSI and ASCII art, but the group later branched out into other artistic media such as music tracking, demo coding, and multimedia software development (e.g. image viewers).\r\n\r\nIn the mid-1990s, ACiD created subsidiary groups responsible for these broader areas. For example, Remorse is the official ACiD sub-label responsible for ASCII art and other text-based graphics. Similarly, pHluid is responsible for module tracking and music production.\r\n\r\nToday, ACiD focuses largely on the preservation of digital art history, talk radio news, and sale of their DVD-based artscene archives.', 'Art', 'Group', 3, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(204, 'Blasphemy', '408 Request Time-out', 724, 'http://www.blasphemy.dk/', NULL, NULL, 'Real-time pixels moving on your monitor.\r\nshould generally work on pentium systems and friends.\r\nlouis lane and newer run natively under win9x/nt,\r\nsome productions should work under plain dos or in a win9x dos-box.', 'Art', 'Group', 2, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', -1),
(205, 'ICE', '200 OK', 754, 'http://www.ice.org/', 'http://www.ice.org/rss.pack.latest.php', NULL, 'iCE is not a pure forum for posting artwork, like other sites. iCE is an art group that has dedicated members (i.e. are not members of any other digital art group) who choose to release their art with us. Every month we gather the art that our members have drawn and package it up and put it on the web site. Making an account on ice.org does not make you an "iCE Member", although it does allow you have to an identity here. To go on to become an iCE Member you need to go through a formal application process and be accepted. It is very hard to get into iCE - we only accept the best out there.', 'Art', 'Group', 5, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(206, 'Logo Factory', '200 OK', 358, 'http://logofactory.planet-d.net/', NULL, NULL, 'Planetary colonisation has begun, cars powered by nuclear-batteries fly between the miles-high skyscrapers, Earth has become a province of the human specie.\r\nPirate-artists, self-called "demosceners", hijacks the huge video screens all around the city to show their latest productions. Meanwhile, the warez-scene is still active, infiltrating the megacorporations and releasing non-stop every bit of new information.\r\nIn all this mess, and since 2001 A.D., a collective of graphists produces high-quality logos and visual identity for those dark-sided movements.\r\nThis collective, code-named LGF, is the Logofactory.', 'Art', 'Underground', 1, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', -1),
(207, 'Intro Zone PC', '301 Moved Permanently - <a href="http://www.easyspace.com/">http://www.easyspace.com/</a>', NULL, 'http://members.easyspace.com/erekose/', NULL, NULL, 'What are Intro''s? - In short, they''re small advertisements for BBS''s (Bulletin Boards(remember them?)), or pirate/demo groups. Long answer: intro''s are a blend of art and technology, they require programming finesse, a desire to produce the tightest, most efficient code, a large amount of skill, and a fair amount of artistic flair and talent. They are the bridge between the ''warezscene'' and the demoscene.', 'Art', 'Underground', NULL, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', -1),
(208, 'Superior Art Creations', '302 Moved Temporarily - <a href="/?01fb9048">/?01fb9048</a>', 692, 'http://www.superiorartcreations.com', NULL, NULL, 'Superior Art Creations, often referred to as SAC, is an underground artscene group which caters primarily to and is well known within the warez scene. During the mid to late nineties most of the notable ANSI artscene groups had distanced themselves from the warez scene, rather creating art for the sake of art, or for bulletin boards that were purely artscene related. Seizing this opportunity, SAC moved into this vacant territory and quickly became recognized as the leading group of warez scene artists. Towards the late 1990s, a good majority of NFO file ASCII art was created by various members of SAC. In 1999, lead ASCII artist Ferrex ascended into the role of senior staff and leader, continuing to control the group to this day.', 'Art', 'Group', 1, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(210, 'BBS Intro Collection', '200 OK', 1198, 'http://bbsintros.vantage.ch/', NULL, NULL, 'This collection was made for all the people out there that can''t forget about their BBS times.', 'Art', 'Collections', 2, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(212, 'Chemical Reaction', '200 OK', 805, 'http://www.chemical-reaction.de/', NULL, NULL, 'A diskmag that should be built of the finest scene artwork in the categories ascii/ansi/gfx/tracks/demos. A diskmag that should separate itself from the warez-scene and build its own art-scene. A diskmag that should be the mag of the mags. So in the year of our Lord 1997 CHEMICAL-rEACTION (cRO) was born ... a new star was flashing on the scene-sky. Their founders soon brought the artist group to rise up as one of the biggest and most legendary ever in the PC-scene. This was mostly done by aquiring very experienced and famous members like hETERO, bATE, pALEDETH or fLI7E.', 'Art', 'Group', 3, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(214, 'Equinox', '200 OK', 712, 'http://equinox.planet-d.net/', NULL, NULL, 'An old Atari ST demo crew that have been recently converting their demo''s to web friendly Java.', 'Art', 'Group', 4, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(215, 'Raster Group', '200 OK', 702, 'http://www.rasterized.org/', NULL, NULL, ' Alot of people ask us what exactly is Raster? Since its inception back in 2001, Raster has continued to grow and evolve far beyond anything we could have ever hoped for. Raster is an art group, deep rooted in the digital art revolution opened up to a large extent by the internet and computers. Raster embraces all forms and mediums of art. Bringing together members from all over the world for one goal. To make good art.', 'Art', 'Group', 5, 0, '2003-01-22 00:00:00', 0),
(216, 'Gameguru Mania', '200 OK', 1072, 'http://www.ggmania.com', 'http://www.ggmania.com/rss.php3', NULL, 'GGMania (formerly gameguru.box.sk) was launched in fall 1999, with the goal of becoming the world''s best online information resource for PC gaming enthusiasts.', 'Gaming', 'News', 0, 0, '2003-02-16 00:00:00', 0),
(218, 'UGN Security', '200 OK', 803, 'http://www.undergroundnews.com/', NULL, NULL, 'A large online community specializing in Text Files and other Files for download.  With features like a large BBS and IRC Server and a killer design, its no wounder that UGN Security is so large.  With over 50 new board registrationg a month (notincluding the lurkers) it can be a "cool" place to spend a warm summers night..', 'Old School', 'Information', 3, 0, '2003-03-19 00:00:00', 0),
(219, 'NFO Temple', '200 OK', NULL, 'http://nfotemple.cjb.net/', NULL, NULL, 'This site is dedicated to the humble NFO file. There are over 1,500 different files from the hacking, cracking, pirate, movie and various scenes. Whats more is they are all viewable online!', 'Old School', 'Information', 2, 0, '2003-03-25 00:00:00', -1),
(220, 'Text Files', '200 OK', 729, 'http://www.textfiles.com/', 'http://ascii.textfiles.com/index.rdf', NULL, 'What this site offers is a glimpse into the history of writers and artists bound by the 128 characters that the American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII) allowed them. The focus is on mid-1980''s textfiles and the world as it was then, but even these files are sometime retooled 1960s and 1970s works, and offshoots of this culture exist to this day.', 'Old School', 'Information', 5, 0, '2003-03-25 00:00:00', 0),
(221, 'GameBird.dk', '408 Request Time-out', 928, 'http://gamebird.dk/', NULL, NULL, 'At this point, GameBird.dk provides you with over 650 classic computer games. Our ambition is to make it possible to find and discuss every old computer game you can imagine. GameBird.dk is a fast, reliable and rapidly growing English-language website, which is easy to survey, and where the games are as easy to install as possible.', 'Old School', 'Abandonedware', 3, 0, '2003-03-25 00:00:00', -1),
(222, 'Old Games at BGBest', '200 OK', NULL, 'http://oldgames.bgbest.net/', NULL, NULL, 'Multilanguage international DOS games portal. With well over a thousand games for downloads including reviews, screenshots etc. The only problem is I have a terrible time connecting to their servers. Slow.', 'Old School', 'Abandonedware', 3, 0, '2003-03-25 00:00:00', -1),
(223, 'C:DOS Community', '200 OK', 9237, 'http://www.cdosabandonware.com/', NULL, NULL, 'C:DOS Community is a abandonware community for abandonware-lovers who likes to share their interest with many others online on the Internet. Here you will find everything you need to run and complete your favourite games. Applications, walkthroughs, manuals, cheats, trainers and of course the games are available here and all you have to do to get access to these files is to register - for free.', 'Old School', 'Abandonedware', 4, 0, '2003-03-25 00:00:00', 0),
(224, 'Home Of The Underdogs', '200 OK', 921, 'http://www.the-underdogs.info', NULL, NULL, 'Home of the Underdogs is a non-profit site dedicated to the preservation and promotion of underrated PC games (and a few non-PC games) of all ages: good games that deserve a second chance after dismal sales or critical reviews that we feel are unwarranted. By nature, our criteria for choosing games to be honored here are subjective. However, we believe that our collective experience (many of us started gaming in late 1970s) allows us to be confident of our choices: we''ve played many of the best and worst games ever made.', 'Old School', 'Abandonedware', 5, 0, '2003-03-25 00:00:00', -1),
(225, 'Thuglife', '200 OK', 706, 'http://www.thuglife.org', 'http://www.thuglife.org/forum2/cgi-bin/yabb/YaBB.cgi?action=rss', NULL, 'Our projects with thuglife.org is to build it up as the only good ascii archive around, with news, files and more. We have programmed it in Perl/Cgi/Html to make it more usefull and the pages will update themselfs.', 'Art', 'ascii', 4, 0, '2003-07-26 00:00:00', 0),
